� Exam Questions & Answers 
Q1: What is @RestController? 
Answer: 
• Combination of @Controller + @ResponseBody 
• Automatically converts return values to JSON 
• Used for building REST APIs 
• No need to use @ResponseBody on each method 
Q2: Difference between @Controller and @RestController? 
@Controller 
@RestController 
Returns view name (HTML) Returns data (JSON/XML) 
Used with @ResponseBody @ResponseBody included 
For MVC apps 
For REST APIs 
Returns String → view 
Returns String → JSON 
Q3: What is ResponseEntity? 
Answer: 
• Represents entire HTTP response (status, headers, body) 
• Allows setting HTTP status codes 
• More control over response 
Example: 
java 
return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.OK).body(student); 
return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND).body("Not found"); 
Q4: What are @RequestBody and @PathVariable? 
@RequestBody: 
• Binds HTTP request body to Java object 
• Used in POST, PUT methods 
• Example: @PostMapping public void add(@RequestBody Student 
student) 
@PathVariable: 
• Extracts values from URI path 
• Used in GET, PUT, DELETE with IDs 
• Example: @GetMapping("/{id}") public Student get(@PathVariable 
int id) 
Q5: What is @Service annotation? 
Answer: 
• Marks class as Service layer (business logic) 
• Detected by component scanning 
• Enables dependency injection 
• Separates business logic from controller 
Q6: Why use Service layer? 
Answer: 
• Separation of Concerns - Controller handles HTTP, Service handles logic 
• Reusability - Service methods can be used by multiple controllers 
• Testability - Easy to test business logic independently 
• Maintainability - Changes to logic don't affect controller 
Q7: What HTTP methods are used for CRUD? 
Operation HTTP Method 
Create 
POST 
Read 
GET 
Update PUT 
Delete 
DELETE 
Example 
Register student 
View students 
Update student 
Delete student 
Q8: What is the purpose of @RequestMapping? 
Answer: 
• Maps HTTP requests to controller methods 
• Can be at class level (base path) and method level 
• Example: @RequestMapping("/students") at class level 
Q9: Explain the architecture of this application. 
Answer: 
Client (Postman) 
↓ 
REST Controller (@RestController) 
↓ 
Service Layer (@Service) 
↓ 
Data Storage (In-Memory List) 
Layers: 
1. Controller - Handles HTTP requests/responses 
2. Service - Business logic and data manipulation 
3. Storage - In-memory ArrayList (can be replaced with database) 
Q10: What is @Autowired? 
Answer: 
• Enables automatic dependency injection 
• Spring creates and injects required objects 
• No need to manually create objects 
• Example: @Autowired private StudentService studentService; 
Q11: How to test REST API without Postman? 
Answer: You can use: 
• cURL (command line) 
bash 
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/students \ -H "Content-Type: application/json" \ -d '{"studentId":101,"name":"John",...}' 
• Browser (for GET only) 
• Swagger UI 
• JUnit tests 
Q12: What is the difference between PUT and POST? 
POST 
PUT 
Create new resource Update existing resource 
Not idempotent 
Idempotent 
/students 
/students/{id} 
Returns 201 Created Returns 200 OK 
Q13: Why use in-memory storage instead of database? 
Answer: Advantages: 
• ✅ Simple and fast for learning/testing 
• ✅ No database setup required 
• ✅ No configuration needed 
• ✅ Quick prototyping 
Disadvantages: 
• ❌ Data lost on restart 
• ❌ Not suitable for production 
• ❌ No persistence 
For production: Replace ArrayList with database (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.) 
Q14: How to add database instead of in-memory storage? 
Answer: 
1. Add dependencies (spring-boot-starter-data-jpa, mysql-connector) 
2. Add @Entity, @Id to Student.java 
3. Create StudentRepository extends JpaRepository 
4. Configure database in application.properties 
5. Use repository in service instead of ArrayList 
Q15: What is the flow when POST request is made? 
Answer: 
1. Client sends POST request with JSON body 
2. Spring converts JSON to Student object (@RequestBody) 
3. Controller receives Student object 
4. Controller calls studentService.registerStudent() 
5. Service adds student to ArrayList 
6. Service returns student object 
7. Controller creates ResponseEntity with status 201 
8. Spring converts response to JSON 
9. Client receives JSON response with status code 
�
� Troubleshooting 
Issue 1: Application won't start 
Error: Port 8080 is already in use 
Solution: Change port in application.properties: 
properties 
server.port=8081 
Issue 2: 404 Not Found for all endpoints 
Solution: 
• Ensure base URL is correct: http://localhost:8080/students 
• Check @RestController and @RequestMapping are present 
• Verify application started successfully 
Issue 3: JSON parsing error in Postman 
Error: Cannot deserialize 
Solution: 
• Check JSON syntax (proper quotes, commas) 
• Verify Content-Type header: application/json 
• Ensure field names match Student class 
Issue 4: Data disappears after restart 
Solution: 
• This is expected (in-memory storage) 
• Data is stored in ArrayList, lost on restart 
• For persistence, use database 
